############################################################################################################
BACKEND
############################################################################################################
	



This is the server application for the mobile IT project "Duelp".
It uses a rest webservice via JAX-RS/Jersey with an Apache application server.

############################################################################################################

Important Links:

	Eclipse:	http://www.eclipse.org/
	Jersey: 	http://jersey.java.net/
	Tomcat: 	http://tomcat.apache.org/

############################################################################################################


INSTRUCTIONS:

1.) 	Install Eclipse INDIGO.
1.1)	Open Eclipse, go to Help->Install New Software…
1.2)	Select http://download.eclipse.org/releases/indigo in "Work with..."
1.3) 	Install everything from Web,XML, Java EE and OSGi Enterprise Development.


2.) 	Tomcat
2.1) 	Download and install Apache Tomcat. -> http://tomcat.apache.org (Restart Eclipse, if necessary)
2.2) 	You may have to configure Eclipse for using Tomcat at *->Preferences->Server->Runtime Envoirements

3.) 	You may have to renew the Server..
3.1)	Right-click on "Servers" in the Package Explorer.
3.2)	Select "Delete"…
3.3)	Right-click on "duelp-backend" in the Package Explorer.
3.3)	Select->New->Other->Server and click "Next".
3.4) 	Select Apache->Tomcat v.7.0 or higher and click "Next".
3.5) 	Click "Add All>>" and then "Finish".

4.)		Run	
4.1)	Select duelp-backend in Package Explorer and click Run->Run as..->Run on Server.
4.2)	Select your new added server and click finish..
4.3) 	You may see  a "HTTP Status 404 - /duelp-backend/" warning, but that's okay…
4.4) 	Open the your web browser and go to: http://localhost:8080/duelp-backend/rest/hello





